Greenspring Blog




05/01/2014
Posted By:J. Patrick Collins Jr., CFP®, EA
Tagged: Investor Behavior, Tactical Asset Allocation 
A Broken Clock…
John Hussman is a very famous mutual fund manager who made some excellent predictions in the past, forecasting some of the market crashes we have seen in the past decade.  Unfortunately, his song has not changed and he continues to beat his drum about getting out of stocks.  As I read this latest article about why I should get out stocks, I started to think to myself, when does someone start to lose credibility?  According to Morningstar, Hussman’s flagship fund (Hussman Strategic Growth) has generated an annual return of -1.21% per year for the past 10 years.  This trails the overall market (S&P 500) by 8.87% per year during that time period.  To put it another way, if I had put $100,000 into the Hussman Strategic Growth Fund ten years ago I’d have $88,538 today. Conversely, the same investment in the S&P 500 would be worth $261,266.
If Hussman maintains his bearish stance, he’ll be right at some point.  As the saying goes a broken clock is right twice a day.  The market always goes down.  The question is, at what cost?  Missing out on all of the gains we have experienced over the past 5 years will most likely not make up for his avoidance of future losses.  This realization confirms much of our thinking at Greenspring.  No one can predict the future consistently.  Managers like Hussman sound very convincing, but as you look at the data of mutual fund returns, it is hard to argue that their success isn’t almost entirely due to luck.  Understanding this simple fact allows us to focus on the key areas that are under our control:  taxes, costs, diversification and discipline.  


Information contained herein has been obtained from sources considered reliable, but its accuracy and completeness are not guaranteed. It is not intended as the primary basis for financial planning or investment decisions and should not be construed as advice meeting the particular investment needs of any investor. This material has been prepared for information purposes only and is not a solicitation or an offer to buy any security or instrument or to participate in any trading strategy. Past performance is no guarantee of future results.








